ce:section.ce:para:
Here, we developed a simple, green and low-cost way to prepare the polymer functionalized CDs via mussel-inspired chemistry for white LED application. The catechol-terminated hydrophobic PS and hydrophilic PEGMA were gained via typical RAFT polymerization and then grafted onto the surface of N-doping blue CDs under weak base condition by Schiff base condensation/Michael addition reaction (called CD@PEGMA and CD@PS) (Scheme 1
                     ). The obtained CD@PEGMA and CD@PS in the solid state showed excellent optical properties as compared with CDs. Especially, the grafting PS could transfer the hydrophilic CDs into organic solvents because PS chains on CDs was easy to dissolve in organic solvents. As shown in Scheme 2
                     , the transparent polymer bulk nanohybrids with white-light emission were constructed by introducing the blue-emitting CD@PS, and MQ coordinated quantum dots (QDs) with green and red-light in the polymerization process of styrene monomers. The resulted fluorescent nanohybrid was used to fabricate warm WLED (0.32, 0.31; CIE coordinate).

Surprisingly, the polymer surface modification obviously enhanced the PL properties of CDs in solid state as shown in Fig. 5D. The solid CDs also owned a relatively high QY of 12%, indicating its self-quenching-resistance [77]. Obviously, the QYs of polymer-modified solid CDs for CD@PS (15%) and CD@PEGMA (23%) were higher than that of pure CDs (Fig. 6
                        A). In order to study the mechanism of fluorescence enhancement in detail, the PL decay curves of CDs, CD@PS and CD@PEGMA were conducted in solid state, and the corresponding average lifetimes (τ) were obtained to be 5.77, 6.19 and 6.83 ns (see Fig. 6B and Table 1
                        ). We found that the decay of CDs was a bit faster than that of CD@PS and CD@PEGMA, and the detailed biexponential fitting parameters are shown in Table 1. The CD@PS (6.19 ns) and CD@PEGMA (6.83 ns) had a slightly increase in average lifetimes as compared with pure CDs (5.77 ns). The improvements in QYs and lifetimes for solid CD@PS and CD@PEGMA may be attributed to the following reasons: (1) the surface traps of CDs were passivated by polymers, inducing a new surface state which was involved the carbogenic core and the functional groups of polymer [78,79]; (2) the surface modification of polymer reduced the non-radiative transition of electron-hole [80–82]; (3) the introduction of polymer could protect the carbogenic core from the interference of external environment, facilitating the interaction of carbogenic core and functional groups [67,83]; (4) the polymers increased the distance between the adjacent CDs under solid state and prevented their self-quenching.
